.content.
  Rain presents a different case from Lee
  because Lee has been an actor all throughout 
  his celebrity career and has taken up physical roles in 
  the past (e.g. in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Bittersweet_Life">
  A Bittersweet Life</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Good,_the_Bad,_the_Weird">
  The Good, the Bad, the Weird</a>).
  Rain, on the other hand, is known primarily 
  as a music performer and heartthrob actor
  in Korean romantic-comedy dramas (most 
  famously in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Full_House_(2004_TV_series)">
  Full House</a>). By playing Raizo in Ninja 
  Assassin, he took a large step outside of his
  traditional role and basically created a new 
  persona for Western audiences. We observe a
  similar case with Taiwanese musician <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Chou">
  Jay Chou</a>, who portrayed 
  <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kato_(The_Green_Hornet)">
  Kato</a>, a skilled martial artist and genius 
  mechanic, in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Green_Hornet_(2011_film)">
  Green Hornet</a>. Despite their unique careers
  and origins, all three actors have clearly been
  placed under a one definition of Asian male
  created by US media culture: the martial artist.
  These are today's Jackie Chans and Bruce Lees.
  
